MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: cartridges/games/[^/]+/[^/]+Renderer\.tsx
ADVISORY: |
  End-of-game conditions (time up, solve, crash, game over) must be
  gated by a SINGLE `let ending = false` flag checked AND set
  synchronously inside the game loop — not by a celebration flag or
  an async `setTimeout` guard alone.

  Common bug:
    if (elapsed >= timeLimit) {
      floatingText.emit({ text: "TIME'S UP!", ... });
      setTimeout(() => finish(), 700);
      solveCelebrate.active = true; // ❌ wrong flag + fires every frame
    }

  This block fires every RAF frame for 700ms, emitting 40+ duplicate
  floating texts, and the reused `solveCelebrate.active` flag draws
  the "SOLVED!" overlay on top of "TIME'S UP!".

  Fix:
    let ending = false;
    ...
    if (!ending && elapsed >= timeLimit) {
      ending = true;
      floatingText.emit(...);
      setTimeout(() => finish(), 700);
    }
    // Solve path uses the same guard:
    if (isSolved() && !ending) {
      ending = true;
      solveCelebrate.active = true;
      setTimeout(finish, 1600);
    }
    // Input handler blocks on it too:
    if (gameOver || ending) return;

  One flag, set synchronously, checked by every end condition. Never
  reuse a celebration-rendering flag as an input-blocking flag — they
  have different lifetimes and semantics.
